{"cursor":"11053","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Thermal shock' occurs when a thermal gradient causes different parts of an\nobject to expand by different amounts. This differential expansion can be\nunderstood in terms of stress or of strain, equivalently. At some point, this\nstress can exceed the strength of the material, causing a crack to form. If\nnothing stops this crack from propagating through the material, it will cause\nthe object's structure to fail.\n\nFailure due to thermal shock can be prevented by;\n# Reducing the thermal gradient seen by the object, by\n## changing its temperature more slowly increasing the material's thermal\n## conductivity\n# Reducing the material's coefficient of thermal expansion Increasing its\n# strength Introducing built-in compressive stress, as for example in tempered\n# glass Decreasing its Young's modulus Increasing its toughness, by\n## crack tip blunting, i.e., plasticity or phase transformation crack deflection\n","linknr":244,"url":"Thermal_shock","recorded":1362481667,"links":24,"instances":["physics","physics","materials_science","physics"],"pdf":["http://www-mech.eng.cam.ac.uk/profiles/fleck/papers/96.pdf","http://www-mech.eng.cam.ac.uk/profiles/fleck/papers/96.pdf","http://www-mech.eng.cam.ac.uk/profiles/fleck/papers/96.pdf","http://www.ils.uec.ac.jp/~dima/disk.pdf"],"categories":["Materials degradation","Laser science"],"headings":["Effect on materials","Relative robustness of materials","Thermal shock parameter in the physics of solid-state lasers","Examples of thermal shock failure","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/b/c/9bc5ed92268ba6bf1c1104a661015a66.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/c/e/8ce4b16b22b58894aa86c421e8759df3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/a/b/bab51bd9e4c1a4c8114ca135d33ae459.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/c/bccfc7022dfb945174d9bcebad2297bb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/a/3/3a3ea00cfc35332cedf6e5e9a32e94da.png","//upload.w